<F P=100> Dominican Republic </F>
<F P=101> Haiti </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S. Banks Pushed To Reopen in `Next 48 Hours' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    U.S. Banks Pushed To Reopen in `Next 48 Hours' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   FL2406224994 Port-au-Prince Signal FM Radio in French 1030 
GMT 24 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL2406224994 </F>
<F P=104>  Port-au-Prince Signal FM Radio </F>
<F P=105>  French </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The two U.S. banks operating in Port-au-Prince -- 
First National of Boston and Citibank -- closed their doors on 
23 June, following U.S. President Bill Clinton's executive order 
freezing Haitian assets in U.S. banks. These two banks had been 
operating in Haiti for 20 years and ranked fourth and fifth, 
respectively, out of the nine foreign banks operating in Haiti. 
These banks operate under and are subject to Haitian law. A 
reliable financial source has reported that a judicial 
injunction compelling them to reopen or to return their 
customers' assets should reach them in the next 48 hours. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-34870 </DOCNO>
