<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-LAT-94-123 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  24 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Dominican Republic </F>
<F P=101> Haiti </F>
<H3> <TI>   Judge Orders Banks To Reopen </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Judge Orders Banks To Reopen </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA2506002794 Madrid EFE in Spanish 2219 GMT 24 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA2506002794 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Port-au-Prince, 24 Jun (EFE) -- Today, Haitian Lower 
Court Judge Henock Voltaire ordered two U.S. banks, which had 
closed their doors to the public in view of U.S. President Bill 
Clinton's decision to freeze Haitian citizens' accounts, to 
reopen on 27 June. 
  Voltaire issued this decision following a suit filed by the 
Central Bank of Haiti. This decision affects Citibank and Bank 
of Boston branches, which on 22 June notified the Central Bank 
governor of their decision to stop operations. After this 
measure was implemented, the two banks did not open their doors 
on 23 and 24 June. Many citizens went to the banks on those two 
days to try to withdrew money. 
  Judge Voltaire maintained that these two banks cannot close 
their doors due to decisions made by the United States; they are 
subject to Haitian laws because they requested authorization to 
operate in Haiti. He also pointed out that their arguments do 
not have merit in Haiti; hence, they will have to reopen. It 
was reported that the Bank of Boston will open its doors on 27 
June. Meanwhile, no Citibank spokesman could be located to 
respond to Judge Voltaire's decision. 
  Political observers believe the U.S. objective of 
implementing financial sanctions to force the military regime to 
relinquish power has worked against the United States because an 
anti-American feeling prevails in Haiti. 
  Meanwhile, operations at the Scotia Bank proceeded as 
normal, 
but many people went to this bank to withdraw money, fearing the 
bank might close its doors to the public. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

