<F P=100> Ecuador </F>
<H3> <TI>   Supreme Court To Decide Agrarian Law Status </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Supreme Court To Decide Agrarian Law Status </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA2506122794 Quito Voz de los Andes in Spanish 2300 GMT 24 
Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2506122794 </F>
<F P=104>  Quito Voz de los Andes </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From "The Voz Andes Newscast"] </F>
  [Text] The country will learn the Supreme Court 
Constitutional Chamber's ruling on the unconstitutionality of 
the agrarian law dictated by the Court of Constitutional 
Guarantees in approximately three weeks. Constitutional Chamber 
Magistrate Hugo Ordonez has asserted that they will expedite the 
ruling but that this does not mean it will be decided with undue 
haste. 
  [Begin Ordonez recording] I would not like to estimate the 
exact duration of this proceeding because it cannot be 
predetermined. We have to see if it takes the regular course. 
However, I surmise--and I do so only to answer the question you 
say currently concerns the country--that the matter could be 
resolved in approximately three weeks. [end recording] 
  Ordonez stated that the verdict will not depend on the 
magistrates' political leanings but instead on whether the law 
adheres to the Constitution. 

</TEXT>

