<F P=100> MEXICO </F>
<H3> <TI>   Resignation Discussed With Salinas </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Resignation Discussed With Salinas </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA2506023194 Mexico City Radio ACIR Network in Spanish 0000 
GMT 25 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2506023194 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City Radio ACIR Network </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Evening News Panorama" newscast] </F>
  [Text] Interior Secretary Jorge Carpizo McGregor has 
unexpectedly resigned from the post he assumed on 10 January. 
In a letter addressed to the president of the republic, Dr. 
Carpizo McGregor explained that his decision to resign was 
prompted by a political party's unrelenting attempts to tarnish 
the 21 August federal elections. 
  The Presidency of the republic reported that President 
Carlos 
Salinas asked Interior Secretary Carpizo McGregor to reconsider 
his resignation. They talked for several hours in President 
Salinas' office, but no agreement was reached. The president of 
Mexico said he hopes Dr. Carpizo reconsiders his decision, and 
Dr. Carpizo responded: "Give me some time, Mr. President. We 
will discuss this issue again this weekend." This is the 
current state of affairs. 
  There have been reactions from several officials following 
Carpizo's resignation. The National Executive Committee of the 
National Action Party [PAN] regretted Dr. Carpizo's decision and 
asked him to reconsider his decision. PAN Mexican presidential 
candidate Diego Fernandez de Zevallos echoed this request. 
  [Begin Fernandez de Zevallos recording] As a citizen and as 
PAN Mexican presidential candidate, I ask Dr. Carpizo McGregor 
to withdraw his resignation for the good of Mexico. I make this 
request considering my perception of Dr. Carpizo McGregor as an 
exemplary citizen and an honest official who must continue at 
the Interior Secretariat for Mexico's well-being. Thank you, 
that is all. [end recording] 
  PRD [Party of the Democratic Revolution] presidential 
candidate Cuahutemoc Cardenas Solorzano also spoke about 
Carpizo's resignation. Cardenas is currently in Tuxtla 
Gutierrez, Chiapas State. He demanded that Jorge Carpizo 
McGregor explain his reasons for resigning from his post of 
interior secretary, which includes his post as president of the 
General Council of the Federal Electoral Institute. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

