<H3> <TI>   `Subversive' Released, Departs for Spain </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    `Subversive' Released, Departs for Spain </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA2406204394 Havana PRENSA LATINA in Spanish 1917 GMT 24 Jun 
94 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> PA2406204394 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana PRENSA LATINA </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Havana, 24 Jun (PL) -- A Cuban female citizen who 
had been sentenced to five years for subversive crimes flew to 
Spain after local authorities released her before she had served 
her full sentence, PRENSA LATINA confirmed today. 
  The woman is Aurea Genoveva Feria Cao, 51 years old, who was 
sentenced in 1990 for spreading enemy propaganda after her 
activities to destabilize the Cuban Government were proven. 
  Reliable sources reported that the woman was released before 
she had served her full sentence as the result of talks with the 
Spanish Government, particularly Galician authorities. 
  Asked by PRENSA LATINA last night about the Cuban 
authorities' decision to approve her trip to Spain, Feria Cao 
said: I appreciate this gesture very much. 
  Feria Cao, mother of four children, two of whom traveled 
with 
her, said she was not mistreated while in prison but that 
serving time was a very hard thing in her life because she had 
been a housewife. I would rather have served my five-year 
sentence in the state's security installations, she said about 
the time she served in prison. 
  Asked about her plans for the future, she said: I will not 
participate in political activities. She also announced her 
intention to reside in Spain. I will devote myself to my 
children and my home, she said. 

</TEXT>

