<H3> <TI>   Canada Offers Invitation to Counternarcotics Training </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Canada Offers Invitation to Counternarcotics Training </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA2706190094 Havana PRENSA LATINA in Spanish 2149 GMT 24 Jun 
94 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> PA2706190094 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana PRENSA LATINA </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Havana, 24 Jun (PL) -- Canada today invited Cuba to 
participate in a multinational counternarcotics training 
program, as part of the joint efforts against that scourge. 
  Canadian Ambassador Mark Entwistle made the announcement, 
indicating that "drug consumption is an international problem 
that can only be solved through international action and 
coordination." 
  The diplomat said that on Sunday, 26 June, the international 
day against drug consumption will be commemorated. He 
emphasized that his country's sponsorship of the training 
program shows Canada's commitment to the war against drug 
trafficking. 
  According to a note obtained by PRENSA LATINA, the 
counternarcotics agencies of 17 other Latin American and Asian 
nations have also been invited to participate in the course, 
which will be held in the Atlantic Province of New Brunswick 
during two weeks in August. 
  The invitation was made three days after Christine Stewart, 
minister of state for Latin America and Africa, ended a working 
visit to the island. Her visit was described as highly 
constructive by both sides. 
  Precisely on Monday, Ottawa resumed official economic aid to 
Cuba, in line with the plans of the government of Prime Minister 
Jean Chretien to maintain a foreign policy that is more 
independent of the United States and with greater rapprochement 
toward Latin America. 
  According to the training schedule, in the first week there 
will be classes and workshops on the counternarcotics methods 
and procedures used in Canada and in the following week, the 
participants will visit specialized counternarcotics units in 
several Canadian locations. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

