<F P=101> Cuba </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Specialist': AEC Constitutes Step Toward Integration </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    `Specialist': AEC Constitutes Step Toward Integration </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA2706013894 Havana PRENSA LATINA in Spanish 1434 GMT 26 Jun 
94 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> PA2706013894 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana PRENSA LATINA </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Clemente Nicado] </F>
  [Text] Havana, 24 Jun (PL) -- According to Foreign Ministry 
specialist Omar Morales, the spirit of agreement among the 
various Latin American integration mechanisms was reiterated in 
the preparations for the creation of the Association of 
Caribbean States [AEC]. 
  In a statement to PRENSA LATINA, Morales said the 
integrationist trend was evinced during recent meetings held by 
the Latin American Economic System and at the Ibero-American 
Summit. 
  The spirit is very healthy for the hemisphere -- Morales 
said 
-- because it opens the path toward the continent's economic 
unity, which will put the area in a better position to compete 
with blocs in other areas of the world. 
  Morales said the AEC is made up of three regional blocs, the 
Anglo-Caribbean Community (Caricom), the Central American 
Integration System (SICA), and the Group of Three, made up of 
Mexico, Venezuela, and Colombia. 
  We hope this integrationist trend to link all regional blocs 
on the continent, including Mercosur [Common Market of the 
South] (Argentina, Brazil, Paraguay, Uruguay) and the Andean 
Pact (Bolivia, Peru, Ecuador, Venezuela, and Colombia), will 
continue, he added. 
  Morales said he will attend a technical meeting in Caracas 
on 
27 and 28 June to complete the future organization's charter. 
In addition, he said, we will continue to work on new subjects, 
like the AEC's working agenda and formulas for the secretariat's 
structure and operation. 
  He confirmed that a foreign ministers meeting will be held 
on 
29 June in Caracas, where the charter will be approved and the 
date and place for the definitive creation of the AEC will be 
established. 
  So far, Bridgetown, the capital of Barbados, is scheduled to 
begin receiving on 4 July heads of state of member countries to 
form the AEC, which is regarded as an intergovernmental 
organization for regional consensus, consultation, and 
cooperation. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

