<F P=100> Guatemala </F>
<H3> <TI>   Military Law To Make Recruitment Less Discriminatory </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Military Law To Make Recruitment Less Discriminatory </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA2706041294 Guatemala City PRENSA LIBRE in Spanish 24 Jun 
94 p 3 </F>

<F P=103> PA2706041294 </F>
<F P=104>  Guatemala City PRENSA LIBRE </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Army spokesperson Edith Vargas de Marroquin 
announced that the new Military Recruitment Law under discussion 
by Congress will prevent the abuses that have been committed 
while recruiting volunteers for military service. The new Law 
on Military Service will correct the deficiencies that elicited 
protests from the people affected by this action. 
  In view of the various proposals presented by groups who 
consider themselves to be affected by the law presented by the 
Army, it is unlikely that the reforms will be discussed before 
the next Congress is installed. According to the military 
spokesperson, several sectors proposed reforms which actually 
made recruitment more complicated instead of less 
discriminatory, the intended objective. The new Law on Military 
Service includes salaries and incentives for fulfilling this 
constitutional duty to make it seem more like a social concept 
than an obligation. 
  On another subject, the military spokesperson said the Army 
is not protecting six civil patrolmen whose arrest has been 
ordered for their alleged participation in the murder of 
political leader Jorge Carpio Nicolle last year. The Army has 
firmly stated that military personnel involved in criminal 
actions must be tried. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

