  [Text] Panama's oil debt with Venezuela and Mexico, within 
the framework of the San Jose Pact, totals $240 million, and 
paying it will have to be done on a long-term basis, Eduardo 
Linares, deputy planning and economic policy minister, has said. 
  The top government official has said Venezuela is not 
pressuring Panama to pay the debt but, rather, is simply 
requesting the renewal of talks. 
  [Begin recording] [Linares] We have just received an 
official 
communication from the Venezuelan Government stating its 
interest in resuming the talks; therefore, we cannot talk of 
pressure. What does exist is a response to our request as a 
responsible government in order to pay to the debt. 
  [Ortega] To pay in what type of manner? This involves many 
millions. The budget was cut, and there is no money. 
  [Linares] The formulas we have proposed to the Mexican 
Government and the one we could reach with Venezuela if we agree 
to resume negotiations allow the government to pay its debt 
within its capabilities in the long term. There are no 
short-term formulas, to be sure. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

