<F P=100> Haiti </F>
<H3> <TI>   Radio Reports on Cost of Operation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Radio Reports on Cost of Operation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   FL2806210094 Port-au-Prince Signal FM Radio in French 1030 
GMT 27 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL2806210094 </F>
<F P=104>  Port-au-Prince Signal FM Radio </F>
<F P=105>  French </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Receiving Haitian refugees aboard a U.S. ship in 
Jamaica's Kingston Harbor costs $120,000 a day, according to the 
25 June SUN-SENTINEL, a Fort Lauderdale, Florida newspaper. The 
use of a Coast Guard patrol boat to process the Haitian people 
costs $2,100 an hour. 
  A flight hour for each of the six helicopters accompanying 
the patrol boat costs $750, the newspaper reports. The operation 
for relief and repatriation of Haitian refugees constitutes the 
Coast Guard's largest operation since the second World War, a 
U.S. Coast Guard official told the newspaper. According to him, 
there have never been so many U.S. warships, from both the Coast 
Guard and the Navy, on the open sea. Eight U.S. ships, 15 Coast 
Guard patrol boats, and hundreds of immigration service members 
are participating in the relief and repatriation operations. The 
U.S. ship, USNS Comfort, which is anchored in Kingston Harbor, 
is temporarily receiving the Haitian refugees to allow them to 
present their political asylum requests to the United States. 
The Haitians, whose requests have been rejected, are repatriated 
to Port-au-Prince. This is what the SUN-SENTINEL reported on 26 
June. It said that $120,000 is spent daily [pauses] must be 
spent daily on Haitian refugees. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

