<F P=100> Haiti </F>
<H3> <TI>   Chamber President Writes Clinton on Intervention </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Chamber President Writes Clinton on Intervention </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   FL2806185594 Port-au-Prince Radio Metropole in French 1045 
GMT 28 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL2806185594 </F>
<F P=104>  Port-au-Prince Radio Metropole </F>
<F P=105>  French </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Chamber of Deputies President Frantz Robert Monde 
has written President Bill Clinton. As a man of exemplary 
character and deep understanding, I want you to know that the 
Haitian people want peace and well-being and not war and misery. 
Monde writes: They reject dictatorship in any form and only 
want the kind of true democracy that develops over years within 
the framework of their own culture, customs, and history. 
  He continues: Mr. President, why are so many blacks in the 
U.S. Congress so desperate to lead you into military 
intervention against a small, poor, defenseless country? They 
want victory for the U.S. Government and Armed Forces, yet -- as 
Cornet, the French poet, might say -- they remain silent on the 
tragedy of hundreds of thousands of their African brothers dying 
in Rwanda. Monde asks: Mr. President, did you ever question 
their interests and what the Democratic Party has to gain by 
you, as the one representing them at the highest leadership 
level, making this decision? 

</TEXT>

