<H3> <TI>   Roundup of Economic Developments </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Roundup of Economic Developments </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA2806144194 </F>
<F P=103> PA2806144194 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
BFN 

    [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
reports on Nicaraguan economic developments monitored through 28 
June. 
  Presidency Minister Antonio Lacayo on 21 June reported that 
the government, during a meeting with the World Bank 
Consultative Group in Paris, obtained a package of $750 million 
for programs that will be implemented in the next three years, 
and not just in 1994 as was initially reported. He added that 
Nicaragua requested another $180 million but the Consultative 
Group will discuss the request at upcoming meetings. (Managua 
BARRICADA in Spanish 22 Jun 94 p 5) 
  Central Bank President Jose Evenor Taboada announced on 27 
June that the World Bank the previous week granted a $60 million 
credit to support the economic recovery program. He confirmed 
that the IMF on 25 June approved a $173 million loan to help the 
country ease the effects of the structural adjustment program 
that the Chamorro administration has implemented since March 
1992. Taboada added that World Bank, IMF, and international 
community assistance will help the country to stabilize its 
economy. (Panama City ACAN in Spanish 0052 GMT 28 Jun 94) 

</TEXT>

