<F P=100> Venezuela </F>
<H3> <TI>   Central Bank Suspends Sale of Foreign Exchange </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Central Bank Suspends Sale of Foreign Exchange </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA2906153594 Mexico City NOTIMEX in Spanish 0831 GMT 29 Jun 
94 </F>

<F P=103> PA2906153594 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City NOTIMEX </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] Caracas, 29 Jun (NOTIMEX) -- The Venezuelan 
Central Bank suspended the sale of foreign exchange for six days 
in order to adopt new measures to halt profiteering after the 
imposition of exchange and price controls on Monday. 
  Venezuelan President Rafael Caldera on Monday ordered the 
partial suspension of individual rights and the imposition of 
exchange controls as part of a strategy to reverse the decline 
of the economy and overcome the financial crisis. Announcing 
the drastic measures over radio and television, the president 
explained that they were necessary because the seriousness of 
the economic crisis produces "insecurity and distrust," affects 
national life, and threatens to disrupt public peace. 
  An announcement published on Tuesday in the GACETA OFICIAL 
indicated that the sale of dollars will be resumed within six 
days in order to halt the sharp fall of the bolivar against the 
U.S. dollar, the price of which went up 85 bolivares in one 
month. 
  Presidential spokesman Guillermo Alvarez Bajares announced 
that the Council of Ministers will meet today to implement the 
price and exchange controls and adopt other measures. Alvarez 
explained that individual rights were suspended to prevent the 
disruption of public order, "because there are groups interested 
in promoting disturbances," which could not be put down with the 
laws that exist in a de jure state. 
  Venezuelans awoke yesterday amid great uncertainty because, 
although price increases were prohibited, merchants "speedily" 
changed the prices of products. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

