<F P=100> Brazil </F>
<H3> <TI>   Amorim Meets Vietnamese Official, Announces Accord </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Amorim Meets Vietnamese Official, Announces Accord </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PY2806201294 Sao Paulo GAZETA MERCANTIL in Portuguese 27 Jun 
94 p 3 </F>

<F P=103> PY2806201294 </F>
<F P=104>  Sao Paulo GAZETA MERCANTIL </F>
<F P=105>  Portuguese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Maria Helena Tachinardi in Brasilia] </F>
  [Text] Upon meeting with Vietnamese Deputy Prime Minister 
Phan Van Khai on 24 June, Brazilian Foreign Celso Amorim 
announced that Brazil and Vietnam will sign a framework trade, 
economic, scientific, and technological cooperation agreement by 
the end of 1994. 
  The Brazilian Government is also requesting that Vietnam 
agree to the appointment of Italo Zappa as the Brazilian 
ambassador to Hanoi. President Franco has already authorized the 
opening of an embassy in Vietnam. 
  Since late last year, Vietnam has expressed interest in 
expanding its relations with Brazil. Vietnam sent Deputy 
Foreign Minister Le Mai first, and then Van Khai. In return, 
Itamaraty sent a trade delegation to Hanoi in April. 
  On 23 June, Khai visited Sao Paulo to hold talks with 
representatives of Maxion [agricultural machinery manufacturer], 
the CBPO [Companhia Brasileira de Projetos Obras] construction 
firm, the Odebrecht construction group, the Brazilian 
Agribusiness Association (ABAG), Ericsson [manufacturer of 
telecommunications and lighting equipment], Braspetro [Petrobras 
International Inc.], Baldan, and Marchezan [manufacturers of 
agricultural equipment]. Vietnam is interested in purchasing 
agricultural machinery, including harvesters. 
  Representatives of leading Brazilian construction companies 
attended a luncheon hosted at Itamaraty for Phan Van Khai. The 
Vietnamese market is potentially significant for Brazilian firms 
that are already established in Southeast Asia. The "chairman" 
of the Chinese company that is building the Three Gorges 
hydroelectric plant, the largest in the world, will arrive in 
Brazil on 4 July. Brazilian construction firms could form a 
consortium to participate in the Chinese project. 

</TEXT>

